<article>
    <h1>RCEP a step to bet&#xAD;ter trade</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-09"><time>2021-01-09</time></a>
        - <span>NEWS FOCUS ASIAN INSIDER</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Dzul­fiqar Fathur Rah­man The Jakarta Post, In­done­sia</p>
    <p>Last year marked the broad­en­ing and deep­en­ing of In­done­sia’s trade re­la­tions with its key part­ners as they con­cluded the long-awaited RCEP amid cool­ing global trade due to the pan­demic.</p>
    <p>The world’s largest trade deal rep­re­sents al­most one-third of the global econ­omy.</p>
    <p>The trade deal is im­por­tant for In­done­sia be­cause the par­tic­i­pat­ing coun­tries col­lec­tively ac­counted for 56.1 per cent of In­done­sia’s to­tal ex­ports and 94.4 per cent of to­tal im­ports in Oc­to­ber, ac­cord­ing to Sta­tis­tics In­done­sia.</p>
    <p>Some coun­tries, in­clud­ing In­done­sia, are ex­pected to rat­ify the RCEP this year.</p>
    <p>The RCEP will en­ter into force 60 days af­ter six Asean mem­ber states and three of its part­ners rat­ify the agree­ment and no­tify the Asean sec­re­tary-gen­eral.</p>
    <p>Once the agree­ment takes ef­fect, the RCEP is ex­pected to raise In­done­sia’s gross do­mes­tic prod­uct by 0.05 per cent by 2032, ac­cord­ing to an es­ti­mate from the In­done­sian Fis­cal Pol­icy Agency.</p>
    <p>Be­cause the RCEP cov­ers in­vest­ment as well, In­done­sia is also ex­pected to see some spillover of for­eign di­rect in­vest­ment, as man­u­fac­tur­ing hubs Thai­land and</p>
    <p>Viet­nam have been show­ing over­ca­pac­ity.</p>


